<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between current yield and yield to maturity?", answer: "Current yield is simply the annual coupon payment divided by the market price. Yield to maturity (YTM) accounts for all future coupon payments plus the gain or loss if you hold the bond to maturity and receive the face value. YTM is a more complete measure of return because it considers the time value of money." },
  { question: "What is a bond coupon rate?", answer: "The coupon rate is the annual interest rate stated on the bond when it is issued. It determines the fixed dollar amount of interest the bond pays each year. A bond with a $1,000 face value and a 5% coupon rate pays $50 per year in interest, typically in two semi-annual payments of $25." },
  { question: "Why do bond prices and yields move in opposite directions?", answer: "When market interest rates rise, existing bonds with lower coupon rates become less attractive, so their prices fall to offer competitive yields. When rates fall, existing bonds with higher coupons become more valuable, pushing their prices up. This inverse relationship is fundamental to bond investing." },
  { question: "What is a premium bond vs. a discount bond?", answer: "A premium bond trades above its face value because its coupon rate is higher than prevailing rates. A discount bond trades below face value because its coupon rate is lower than current rates. At maturity, both return the face value, which affects total return calculations." },
  { question: "How often do bonds pay interest?", answer: "Most bonds pay interest semi-annually (twice per year). Some bonds pay annually, quarterly, or monthly. The payment frequency affects both the yield to maturity calculation and the actual return you receive." }
]) %>

