    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Bond Yield Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Enter the bond face value (typically $1,000), coupon rate, current market price, years remaining until maturity, and payment frequency. The calculator instantly computes the current yield, yield to maturity (YTM), annual coupon payment, and per-period coupon payment. It also tells you whether the bond trades at a premium, discount, or par.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding bond yields is essential for fixed-income investors. The current yield gives you a quick snapshot of the income return, while the yield to maturity provides the total expected return if you hold the bond until it matures, accounting for both coupon payments and any capital gain or loss from the difference between market price and face value.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Bond Yield Metrics</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>current yield</strong> is calculated as the annual coupon divided by the market price. It tells you the income return at today's price but ignores capital gains or losses at maturity. The <strong>yield to maturity (YTM)</strong> is the total return anticipated if the bond is held until maturity, accounting for coupon payments, reinvestment, and the difference between purchase price and face value. YTM is calculated using an iterative method (Newton's method) since there is no closed-form solution.
      </p>

      <h3>Premium, Discount, and Par Bonds</h3>
      <p>
        A bond trading above face value is a premium bond, meaning its coupon rate exceeds current market rates. A discount bond trades below face value, indicating the coupon rate is below market rates. A par bond trades at face value. Understanding this relationship helps investors evaluate whether a bond is fairly priced relative to current interest rate conditions.
      </p>

      <h3>Factors That Affect Bond Yields</h3>
      <p>
        Bond yields are influenced by prevailing interest rates, credit quality of the issuer, time to maturity, inflation expectations, and market supply and demand. Higher credit risk bonds offer higher yields to compensate investors. Longer-term bonds typically yield more than shorter-term bonds, a phenomenon known as the term premium.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the difference between current yield and yield to maturity?</h3>
      <p>Current yield is the annual coupon divided by market price. YTM accounts for all future coupon payments plus any capital gain or loss at maturity, providing a more complete picture of total return.</p>

      <h3>What is a bond coupon rate?</h3>
      <p>The coupon rate is the annual interest rate that determines the fixed payments the bond makes. A $1,000 bond with a 5% coupon pays $50 per year.</p>

      <h3>Why do bond prices and yields move in opposite directions?</h3>
      <p>When rates rise, existing lower-coupon bonds become less attractive, so prices fall. When rates fall, higher-coupon bonds become more valuable, pushing prices up.</p>

      <h3>What is a premium bond vs. a discount bond?</h3>
      <p>A premium bond trades above face value because its coupon exceeds current rates. A discount bond trades below face value because its coupon is below current rates.</p>

      <h3>How often do bonds pay interest?</h3>
      <p>Most bonds pay semi-annually. Some pay annually, quarterly, or monthly. The frequency affects the YTM calculation.</p>

